Lawyers for Jasvir argued that he is the only son of his parents, and that he and his wife had only been married eight months when they were arrested.

Indian justice officials had originally rejected the plea because of the seriousness of the crime. 

But they overturned the earlier ruling in the broader public interest saying that the right to life and personal liberty under Article 21 of the Constitution includes the right of convicts and jail inmates to have conjugal visits or artificial insemination in order to have children.

